# WEDNESDAY FEB 11
schedule_post "2026-02-11T08:30:00.000Z" "Resale was the disruptor. Now it's being disrupted.\\n\\nThe 2010s narrative was simple: circular is the future, Gen Z loves sustainability, resale platforms will eat fast fashion's lunch.\\n\\nAll true. But incomplete.\\n\\nWhat nobody modeled: authentication costs don't scale linearly. Every luxury item needs expert verification. At volume, that's a massive cost center. The RealReal's margin pressure isn't a demand problem—it's an operations problem.\\n\\nAdd oversupply of hype products (Yeezy flooding the market), platform fatigue (how many apps can consumers maintain?), and luxury brands launching their own resale channels.\\n\\nThe standalone resale platforms that survive will have either proprietary authentication tech or exclusive brand partnerships. Everyone else is commodity."

schedule_post "2026-02-11T12:30:00.000Z" "Why luxury brands are building resale instead of fighting it:\\n\\n→ Capture margin from the second transaction\\n→ Control authentication standards\\n→ Access customer data from secondary buyers\\n→ Protect brand perception (no fakes in \"official\" resale)\\n\\nGucci Vault, Richemont's Watchfinder, Prada's pre-owned program—these aren't sustainability gestures. They're vertical integration.\\n\\nThe playbook: sell once at full price, capture resale commission, maintain brand control.\\n\\nStandalone platforms are now competing with the brands whose products they sell. That's a structural disadvantage."

schedule_post "2026-02-11T18:30:00.000Z" "Three predictions for resale in 2025:\\n\\n1. At least one major resale platform gets acquired by a luxury conglomerate—not for the brand, but for the authentication infrastructure.\\n\\n2. Authentication tech becomes the differentiator. Computer vision + spectroscopy at scale. Platforms without it become marketplaces with quality problems.\\n\\n3. Brand-owned resale captures 30%+ of secondary market volume in luxury categories. Standalone platforms pivot to mid-market or niche verticals.\\n\\nThe circular economy thesis remains correct. But the business model is consolidating."

# THURSDAY FEB 12
schedule_post "2026-02-12T08:30:00.000Z" "The China luxury story everyone's telling: consumption collapsed, youth are broke, luxury is doomed.\\n\\nThe real story: consumption fragmented across channels and geographies, and most brands are still optimizing for the old pattern.\\n\\nHere's what's actually happening:\\n\\nDomestic luxury spending in China is softer than 2019, but not catastrophic. The duty-free Hainan island strategy is working—luxury malls are packed. And Chinese travelers are back, but they're shopping in Japan (weak yen = 20-30% discount on European brands) instead of Europe.\\n\\nThe customer didn't disappear. The location did.\\n\\nBrands optimizing for 2019's \"wealthy Chinese tourist in Paris\" model are seeing numbers drop. Brands with strong Hainan presence and Japan inventory are quietly winning."

schedule_post "2026-02-12T12:30:00.000Z" "Why Japan is becoming China's luxury shopping mall:\\n\\n→ Yen at multi-decade lows = 20-30% effective discount\\n→ Geographic proximity = short trips possible\\n→ Weaker import restrictions than Europe\\n→ Xiaohongshu culture amplifies the \"smart shopping\" narrative\\n\\nChinese travelers in Japan spend more per capita on luxury than Japanese locals. And they post about it, creating a feedback loop.\\n\\nThe luxury brands seeing soft China numbers in Q3? Many of them had inventory and marketing optimized for Shanghai and Paris. Not Tokyo.\\n\\nGeographic strategy matters more than ever."

schedule_post "2026-02-12T18:30:00.000Z" "Three implications of China's fragmented luxury market:\\n\\n1. Same-store sales in Chinese malls will underperform for years. The traffic is never coming back to that format. Hainan and cross-border are the new normal.\\n\\n2. Japan needs to be treated as a China-adjacent market, not a domestic one. Chinese language service, payment integration, and inventory planning should reflect this.\\n\\n3. The brands winning are those with flexible geographic strategy. LVMH and Hermès can shift inventory and marketing spend across regions. Smaller brands stuck in long-term boutique leases are trapped in the wrong locations.\\n\\nThe China customer is still spending. The question is whether you're where they're shopping."

# FRIDAY FEB 13
schedule_post "2026-02-13T08:30:00.000Z" "The sneaker resale market contracted 25%+ from its 2021 peak. Most analysts blame the economy. They're half right.\\n\\nThe real driver: brands killed their own golden goose.\\n\\nWhen resale margins hit 300-500% on limited drops, brands saw lost revenue, not market validation. Their response? Increase supply, add restocks, widen distribution.\\n\\nScarcity requires restraint. Public companies don't do restraint well.\\n\\nThe result: resale prices collapsed, but so did the cultural capital. When everyone can get the shoe, nobody wants it. Nike's DTC push trained customers to expect access, not earn it.\\n\\nThe brands winning now—New Balance, Asics, niche running labels—understand that cultural cache compounds slowly and evaporates quickly."

schedule_post "2026-02-13T12:30:00.000Z" "Why Nike's SNKRS app became a case study in algorithmic fatigue:\\n\\nThe promise: exclusive access for true fans.\\n\\nThe reality: bots, crashes, and a lottery system that trained customers to expect disappointment.\\n\\nWhen scarcity becomes randomness, the game stops being fun. The psychological reward of \"winning\" a drop requires the possibility of losing. But SNKRS made losing so common that participation dropped.\\n\\nMeanwhile, New Balance releases a few excellent collaborations annually. No app required. No lottery. Just consistent quality and organic demand.\\n\\nThe lesson: algorithms can distribute product, but they can't manufacture desire. That still requires human judgment and restraint."

schedule_post "2026-02-13T18:30:00.000Z" "Three shifts in sneaker economics for 2025:\\n\\n1. The collaboration bubble is popping. 47 Travis Scott drops later, the market is exhausted. Future wins will be rare, not frequent.\\n\\n2. Running technology (carbon plates, foam compounds) is the new design language. Performance credibility beats celebrity association.\\n\\n3. Regional exclusives replace global hype. Limited Japan-only or EU-only drops create real scarcity without flooding any single market.\\n\\nThe brands that win will act like private companies with public balance sheets. Long-term cultural investment over quarterly revenue optimization."

